  "unmapped_findings": [
    "Fracture surfaces of all four steels exhibit numerous dimples, indicating ductile fracture mode (Fig. 5).",
    "Engineering stress-strain curves show that total elongation increases with Cr content, while yield strength increases with Ni content; the 2Ni3Cr steel achieves YS>1100 MPa, UTS>1200 MPa, TEL>45%, and a TS×TEL product of 55.36 GPa·%.",
    "Strain hardening rate curves exhibit three stages: Stage I (sharp decrease), Stage II (increase, prolonged with Cr), Stage III (decrease); 2Ni5Cr shows higher hardening rate than 2Ni and 2Ni3Cr in Stage III.",
    "Deformation mechanisms differ: 3Cr steel shows HDDA and dynamic slip band refinement (DSBR) with few deformation twins near fracture; 2Ni steel is dominated by planar slip, no deformation twins, only stacking faults at very high strain.",
    "First-principles calculations indicate that Cr addition increases formation energy of κ-carbides (e.g., Cr21(FeC3)2 formation energy -0.049 eV/atom vs. -0.160 eV/atom for ideal (Fe,Mn)3AlC), thereby suppressing nucleation and growth, while Ni addition reduces formation energy (AlNi3C formation energy -0.181 eV/atom), promoting κ-carbide formation.",
    "Comparing with other steels (Table 2, Fig. 4d), the present Ni&Cr-alloyed Fe-20Mn-9Al-1.5C steels achieve a superior combination of yield strength and total elongation, notably higher yield strength at similar GPa·% levels.",
    "The shear modulus difference between austenite matrix and κ-carbides is estimated as ΔG ≈ 23.3 GPa; the transition radius where dominant precipitation strengthening shifts from ordering to coherency+modulus mismatch is indicated in Fig. 10.",
    "Hall-Petch coefficient for these steels is taken as KHP = 446.8 MPa·μm^0.5; effective grain sizes (including twins) used for calculation are 3.51, 3.73, 3.72, and 2.2 μm respectively.",
    "Solute strengthening components calculated using empirical formula: 279[C] - 1.5[Mn] + 20.5[Al] + 2.9[Ni] + 3.9[Cr] (all in wt.%), yielding 515.4, 509.5, 557.2, 554.1 MPa for 3Cr, 2Ni, 2Ni3Cr, 2Ni5Cr respectively.",
    "Interrupted tensile tests performed at engineering strains of 3% (or 5%) and 10% to characterize microstructural evolution."
  ]
